  <steps>
    <step order="1">Compare current `package.json` exports map against `@spaarke/events-components` (the canonical reference).</step>
    <step order="2">Add/update exports map to include `./components`, `./widgets`, `./hooks`, `./services`, `./types` (+ default `./`).</step>
    <step order="3">Verify each subpath has the corresponding `src/{name}/index.ts` populated.</step>
    <step order="4">Test from a consumer: `import { DailyBriefingApp } from '@spaarke/daily-briefing-components/components'` resolves; same for each subpath.</step>
    <step order="5">Run `npm run build` on new package + consumers; verify green.</step>
    <step order="6">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 016 status from 🔲 to ✅.</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="npm">Build TypeScript packages.</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="code">src/client/shared/Spaarke.DailyBriefing.Components/package.json</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">Exports map includes `./components`, `./widgets`, `./hooks`, `./services`, `./types`.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Each subpath resolves from a consumer import (build verifies).</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    If the new package's `./widgets` subpath is empty (because all widgets are exported from `./components`), still include it — Pattern D convention is to expose all five subpaths even if one is a passthrough.
  </notes>

